<publishercopyright>© 2014 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.</publishercopyright>
<ce:para>The enzyme taxadiene synthase of the paclitaxel biosynthetic pathway cyclizes geranylgeranyl pyrophosphate (GGPP) to produce taxadiene, which is then believed to be stereo- and regiospecifically oxidized by taxadiene 5α-hydroxylase to form taxadien-5α-ol. However, when the metabolism of Escherichia coli was re-engineered in the present study to express both aforementioned plant enzymes, it was observed that taxadiene 5α-hydroxylase acts on 4 substrates and forms 12 products, of which taxadien-5α-ol is only a minor constituent. Additionally, 2 of the 4 substrates of taxadiene 5α-hydroxylase are products of taxadiene synthase, and it is very likely that this behavior by the two enzymes is independent of the host. Enzyme multispecificity and promiscuity are entirely new propositions in metabolic engineering, and canonical enzyme engineering strategies for modulating the activity of enzymes are largely inapplicable for addressing this phenomenon. To this end, a novel computational methodology was specifically developed to investigate the catalytic mechanism of taxadiene 5α-hydroxylase - hereinafter re-christened as taxadiene monooxygenase - and potentially guide rational re-engineering of its active site. The methodology could be extended to other P450 systems, is faster, and comparably insightful as more elaborate structure-guided approaches such as X-crystallography. In addition, the methodology can also be used to infer the influence of mutations in the active site of the enzyme on its catalytic promiscuity. The insights provided by such computational analyses of multispecificity and promiscuity could greatly enhance the scope and impact of enzyme engineering for over-production of plant secondary metabolites in microorganisms.</ce:para>
